Question:
A jeweller has 12 pieces of chain, each with two links. He wants to make one big closed necklace of them, as shown. To do this he has to open some links (and close them afterwards). What is the smallest number of links he has to open? See image.

Options:
A: \(8\)
B: \(9\)
C: \(10\)
D: \(11\)
E: \(12\)

message.content:
Think in terms of connecting 12 “segments” (each of length 2 links) into one closed loop.

To join 12 segments into a ring, we need 12 connections (each segment must connect to two neighbors).

Each time we open a link, we can use that link to connect two segment ends. So one opened link gives one connection.

However, each 2-link segment has only 2 links available, so from any given segment we can provide at most 2 connections.

We must open at least one link from every segment except possibly one, otherwise some segment would remain unconnected. Thus the minimum possible number is 11.

This can be achieved: take one chosen segment intact; from each of the remaining 11 segments, open exactly 1 link and use it to connect into a growing chain, finally closing it into a loop using the last opened link.

Answer:D
